Introducing this would cause subtle bugs. Say you wrote this:

```js
require('./some-module-with-side-effects');
```

`some-module-with-side-effects` exports a thing called `foo`.  You also want to reference a variable `foo`, but have forgotten to declare it:

```js
'use strict';
require('./some-module-with-side-effects');
doSomething(foo);
```

No exception would be thrown in the above situation, which is bad.

Also: what happens if `global.foo` already exists?

There are quite a few reasons not to do this.

From a quick look it seems that `_read()` is not called for the empty chunk.

https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/82f89ec8c1554964f5029fab1cf0f4fad1fa55a8/test/common/duplexpair.js#L16-L22

As a result the write of the empty chunk does not complete (the callback is not called) and this prevents `_final()` from being called and from pushing the `null` chunk on the client.

https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/82f89ec8c1554964f5029fab1cf0f4fad1fa55a8/test/common/duplexpair.js#L31-L35

This is confirmed by the fact that `'finish'` is not emitted

```js
serverSide.on('finish', common.mustCall());
```

In https://github.com/nodejs/node/pull/29649 it works with `net.Socket` because empty chunks are discarded.

https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/82f89ec8c1554964f5029fab1cf0f4fad1fa55a8/lib/internal/stream_base_commons.js#L196-L198

A possible way to fix the issue is to not push empty chunks

```diff
diff --git a/test/common/duplexpair.js b/test/common/duplexpair.js
index 0783aeb861..ba46e20f5d 100644
--- a/test/common/duplexpair.js
+++ b/test/common/duplexpair.js
@@ -24,8 +24,13 @@ class DuplexSocket extends Duplex {
   _write(chunk, encoding, callback) {
     assert.notStrictEqual(this[kOtherSide], null);
     assert.strictEqual(this[kOtherSide][kCallback], null);
-    this[kOtherSide][kCallback] = callback;
-    this[kOtherSide].push(chunk);
+
+    if (chunk.length) {
+      this[kOtherSide][kCallback] = callback;
+      this[kOtherSide].push(chunk);
+    } else {
+      callback();
+    }
   }
 
   _final(callback) {
```

This is consistent with `net.Socket` behavior but I'm not sure if it masks a bug in `Readable.prototype.read()` implementation.

